const Q_GOVERNMENT_2015=[{"id": "objective>Government>2015>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The tenure of an elected chairman of local government is determined by the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Federal Executive Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Union of Local Government Employees</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Assembly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">State House of Assembly </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Section 7 of the 1999 constitution guaranteed a system of local governments by democratically elected local government councils, but all benefits that are derivable by this constitutional provision, the dividends of democracy, were taken away in the same breadth by the same section of the constitutions tying the LGCs to the state governments' control. The state house of assembly approved a four year tenure for council chairmen and other representatives. The four-year tenure is under the Local Government Administration Amendment Law.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 1976 Reforms made the local government the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">second-tier of government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">first-tier government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fourth-tier government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">third-tier government</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the National guidelines for Local Government Reform published in August 1976 by the Obasanjo Administration aimed mainly at unifying the hitherto multiple system of local government in Nigeria as a strong third-tier of government in practical terms, correct the problems confronting these councils, etc.A lot of changes were carried out in the system of local government in Nigeria. One of the features of the local government reforms in Nigeria is that all the local governments were made the third-tier government after the federal and state government after the federal and state governments. The purpses of establishing the local government majorly was to bring the government closer to the people.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Decision making is the traditional Igbo political system was conferred on the basis of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">privilege</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">age </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gender </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">status </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Igbo political administration was based on the principle of village democracy which thrived on the patrilineal family group known as Umunna. There are two major groups in the village government viz the Council of Elders (Ama-ala) made up of heads of families who held staff of authority called Ofo and the village Assembly made up of all grown-up male members of the village (Ohana-eze). Decisions under this system were reached through consensus and not by voting. Age grades played very useful political role in the Igbo pre-colonial administration. The pre-colonial administration in Igbo land was essential democratic with each village being a small republic. </div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : IGBO PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The political party that originated from Jamiyyar Mutanem Arewa was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UMBC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">BYM</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NEPU</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NPC</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Northern People's Congress (NPC) was founded in Octoer 1951. NPC metamorphosed from the Northerner's Cultural Organization known as Jam'iyyar Mutanen Arewa founded in December 1949. The pary NPC was dominated by the Hausa-Fulanis and had its roots on the Moslem religion of Islam. Its leader was late Sir. Alhaji Ahmadu Bello, the Sardauna of Sokoto, a powerful spiritual and traditional leader. The NPC established absolute political control in the north and had automatic Northerners' allegiance as a result, its strong tradition of obedience to Islam and support of traditional rulers. The aims of NPC includes; to foster the autonomy of the north, to contribute to the social, political and economic development of the north, to educate northerners on their political and civil responsibilities etc.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FIRST REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A major consequence of colonialism on Nigeria is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic dependence </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the attainment of equal status with Europe </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suppression of state structures </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the upliftment of its image </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The scramble for and the partitioning of West Africa by the European nations acted as the genesis of the establishment of colonial administration in West Africa. With the exception of Liberia, the whole West African countries came under the colonial rule of Britain, France, Germany and Portugal- nations that shared out West Africa as a result of its partitioning which took place during the Berlin conference of 1884/1885. The period 1885-1950s served as period of colonial rule in West Africa. The period witnessed economic dehumanization for the peoples of West Africa. However, one of the major consequence of colonial administration in Nigeria is Economic Dependence and Exploitation i.e the colonialists had complete control of the economics of their former colonies as a result of colonial rule. </div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : IMPACT OF BRITISH COLONIAL RULE- ECONOMIC, POLITICAL, SOCIO-CULTURAL"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Judiciary contribute to the development of constitutions through </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judicial review </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">historical records </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bye-laws </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acts of parliament </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Judiciary is the third organ of government responsible for interpretation and application of laws when they are broken or violated. The Judiciary exercises its power in the constitution through Judicial review. Judicial review is a process under which executive and (in some countries) legislative actions are subject to review by the Judiciary. A court with Judicial review power may invalidate laws and decisions that are incompatible with a higher authority, an executive decision may be invalidated for being unlawful or repugnant to a statute, and a statute may be invalidated for violating the terms of a written constitution Judicial review is one of the checks and balances in the separation of powers. The power of the Judiciary to supervise the legislative and executive branches when the latter exceed their authority. The doctrine varies between jurisdictions, so the procedure and scope of Judicial review may differ between and within countries.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTION : TYPES OF CONSTITUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The upper house of the legislature is responsible for the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">assent of bills </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">signing of treaties </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">approval of declaration of war </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passage of appropriation bill </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The upper house of the legislature, also known as the Senate in many countries, is responsible for the assent of bills. This means that before a bill becomes law, it must be approved by the upper house. This process is part of the checks and balances system in a democratic government to ensure that laws are thoroughly reviewed before they are enacted.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : LEGISLATURE TYPES, STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following political parties contested the 1993 Presidential Election? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NRC and SDP</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">AD and APP</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UNCP and NDP</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">PRP and DPP </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Republican Convention (NRC). The political party was registered through the approval of the Armed Forces Ruling Council with Chief Tom Ikimi as its National chairman. The party had its registered offices at the Federal Capital Territory, Abuja. The party sponsored candidates for elections between 1991 - 1993.  <br/>  Social Democratic Party (SDP)  <br/>  It was approved by the Armed Forces Ruling Council with Chief Tomy Aneneh as its National chairman. It had its registered offic in FCT, Abuja. One of its achievements was that it sponsored candidates for elections at all levels of party and government between 1991 and 1993.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FOURTH REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A mode of production in which the resources of a community are pooled are together, for the general well-being of the people is called </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">communism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">communalism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">socialism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capitalism </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Communalism refers to a system of collective ownership of property and cooperation among members of a community in the execution of development projects. In a communal community, members pursue a common goal collectively. Properties like land are owned collectively and shared among members on equal basis. This system of government called Communalism was more predominant in the pre-colonial era.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : SOCIALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of these international organization was Nigeria a founding member?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UNO</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Commonwealth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NATO </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ECOWAS</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic community of West African States (ECOWAS) may be defined as a sub-regional organisation formed by West Africa countries mainly to promote co-operation and development in all economic fields and to contribute to the progress and development of African continent. On the historical date of May 28, 1975, Heads of state and government of 15 independent states of West Africa, converged in Lagos where they signed a treaty formally establishing ECOWAS. It was the initiatives of Nigeria and Togo under the leadership of General Yakubu Gowon and General Gnasingbe Eyadema respectively that saw the establishment of ECOWAS is in Lagos, Nigeria with the inclusion of Capeverde, the community now has 16- member states made up of 5 anglophone and 11 francophone members. These members are  <br/>  Anglophone - Nigeria, Ghana, Sierra leone, Gambia, Liberia <br/> *_Francophone - Togo, Senegal, Ivory coast, Dahomey, Guinea Bissau, Niger republic, Mauritamia, Cape verde, Guinea, Mali, Burkina Faso.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : THE COMMONWEALTH"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's role in ECOWAS was significant in dispute resolution in </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Liberia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Niger </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Gambia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Senegal</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In August 1990, the 16-member Economic Community of West African states (ECOWAS) agreed to deploy a Joint military intervention force, the Economic Community Monitoring Group (ECOMOG) and place it under Nigerin Leadership. The mission later included troops from non-ECOWAS countries, including Uganda and Tanzania. ECOMOG's objecties were to impose a cease-fire help Liberians establish an interim government until elections could be held; stop the killing of innocent civilians and ensure the safe evaluation of foreign nationals. ECOMOG, an ECOWAS intervention force, arrived at the free port of Monrovia on August 24, 1990 landing from Nigerian and Ghanian vessels.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : ECOWAS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An example of civil right of a citizen is the right to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be voted for </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">property and justice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">peace and assembly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vote </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Civil rights are the rights of citizens to political and social freedom and equality. The right to vote is a fundamental civil right in a democratic society. It allows citizens to choose their representatives in government and have a say in the laws and policies that govern them. The other options, while important, are not as directly tied to the concept of civil rights as the right to vote.</div>", "topic": "CITIZENSHIP : CITIZENSHIP RIGHTS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the judical parlance, writ means</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restraining order  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prohibitive order </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acquisiting order </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sentencing order </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A writ is a formal order under seal, issued in the name of a sovereign government, Court or other competent authority, enjoining the officer or other person to whom it is issued or addressed to do or refrain from some specified act. In English common law, a writ is a formal written order issued by a body with administrative or judicial jurisdiction, in modern usage, this body is generally a court. It is a restraining order.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : JUDICIARY FUNCTIONS, POWERS AND COMPONENTS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public corporations are controlled by the legislature through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">daily monitoring of their activities </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discipline of staff </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">approval of their annual budgets </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recruitment of staff</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public corporation is a business organization established, owned, managed and financed with tax payers money by government of a country with the main motive of not making profit but to render essential services to members of the public. The legislature handles the approval of their annual budgets through their parliamentary control.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC CORPORATIONS AND PARASTATALS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the reasons for the adoption of Africa as the centrepiece of Nigeria's foreign policy is to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encourage rivalry in Africa  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopolize Africa economics </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protect her domestic environment </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">challenge the major power </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">By Africa being the centre-piece of Nigeria's foreign policy, it means, Nigeria must first give attention to Africa in its external relations. That is Nigeria identity with and defeat the legitimate interests of Africa. Therefore, Africa serves as the hub from which radiate the spikes of Nigerians foreign policy. Section 19 of the constitution states that the Nigerian state \"shall promote African Unity as well as total political, economic social and cultural liberation of Africa\".</div>", "topic": "RELATIONS WITH AFRICAN COUNTRIES"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elective principle was first introduced in Nigeria by the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lyttleton Constitution </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Richard Constitution </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Clifford Constitution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macpherson Constitution </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Clifford constitution adopted in 1922 deprived its name from the Governor of Nigeria, Sir Hugh Clifford who took over from former governor Lord Lugard. The constitution introduced a new Legislature council and Executive Council which replaced the abolished old legislative council for Lagos colony and the Nigerian council.  <br/>  The constitution introduced elective principle which increased political agitation and awakened the spirit of nationalism in Nigeria. The Northern Nigeria was not represented in the new legislative council, the Governor-General restrained the power to legislated for the North.</div>", "topic": "THE ELECTORAL PROCESS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The type of pressure group that champions the interest and the rights of the under privileged is known as the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">professional pressure groups </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promotional interest group </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic interest group </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">educational pressure group </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The promotional pressure groups promote some causes which may not directly benefit their members, but for the less privileged in the society. They are out to secure improved conditions of the people's welfare e.g National council for Eradication of Illiteracy, Anti-slave trade etc</div>", "topic": "PRESSURE GROUPS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A major innovation of the 1979 Constitution was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase in the constitutional powers of elected officials </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">creation of more states </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prohibition of cross-carpeted </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">introduction of presidential system </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The second Republican constitution of 1979 had one major innovation which was that the constitution jettisoned the parliamentary system of government and introduced the presidential system of government similar to the United states of America.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The organ of the AU that prepares for the meeting of the Assembly of Heads of State and Government is the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Commission of Mediation, Conciliation and Arbitration </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">African Parliament </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Council of Ministers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">General Secretariat </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Council of Ministers consists of foreign ministers or delegated Ministers of member-states. The council meets twice a year but may meet in an extraordinary session at the request at the request of any member-state provided two-thirds majority member-states approve it. Each member state has one vote and two-thirds of the total membership constitute a quorum for any meeting. This organ is directly responsible to the Assembly of Heads of state and Government.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : AU"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the major features of a fascist government is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Political power is decentralised </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it gives room for opposition </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the state defines the rights of individuals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sovereignty is identical with landed property </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fascism is a form of radical authoritarian nationalism that came to prominence in early 20th-century Europe, influenced by national syndicalism. Fascism originated in Italy during World War 1 and spread to other European Countries Fascism opposes liberalism Marxim and anarchism. It believes that liberal democracy is obsolete and they regard the complete mobilization of society under a totalitarian one-party state as necessary to prepare a nation for armed conflict and to respond effectively to economic difficulties . It however has disdain for the recognition of human rights.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : FASCISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Promotion and discipline of civil servants is the responsibility of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Federal Character Commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministry of Labour </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Civil Service Commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public Complaints Commission </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The civil service is a body or department in the executive arm of the government responsible for the execution of the policies and programmes of the government. The civil service and its workers known as civil servants perform purely administrative and executive functions which entail formulation and implementation of government policies. The civil service is divided into departments and are called ministries headed by Ministers of commissioners who serve both as political and executive head. The promotion and discipline of civil servants is the responsibility of the public service commission which is a body vested with the powers of appointment, promotion, transfers, discipline and dismissal of civil servants. </div>", "topic": "THE CIVIL SERVICE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Under the unitary arrangement, the centre is vested with </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">limited power over the constitution units</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equal power with the constituent units </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">insignificant power </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">absolute power </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Unitary system is one in which all governmental powers are concentrated in the hands of a single authority or central government. The central government is the only source from which power emanates. A unitary constitution which is guided by the principle of Unitarism. Countries that adopt Unitary system are Britain, Italy, France, Belgium, New Zealand, Sweden, Ghana etc.</div>", "topic": "STRUCTURES OF GOVERNANCE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of these international organizations is Nigeria a member major because of her economic interest?  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UN</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Commonwealth </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">AU</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OPEC</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Organisation of Petroleum Exporting countries (OPEC) was formed in 1960 to promote and protect the interest of its members. The outcome of the September 10 - 14, 1960 meeting of Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela aimed at protecting the mutual interest and counter the atrocious act of foreign oil companies which produce and sell oil in accordance with their own interest and the dictates of their governments, foreign policies, was the formation of the OPEC. Nigeria joined OPEC majorly because of her economic interest.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OPEC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abolition of civil liberty is an attitude of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">presidential government </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">parliamentary government </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">military government </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">republic government </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The military rule did not give room for civil liberty as there was extreme violation of human rights. The military administrations no matter how humane, indulged in denying the citizens their fundamental human rights where people are detained with impunity and without trial.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : PRESIDENTIAL SYSTEM OF GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the agencies introduced by the military to promote national integration was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Youth Service Corps </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Directorate of Mass Mobilization for Social and Economic Reconstruction </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Directorate of Food, Roads and Rural infrastructure </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Directorate for Employment </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The National Youth Service Corps programme was established in 1973 during the administration of General Yakubu Gowon, at a time when people of Nigeria at the end of the civil war were afraid, to go , live and work in other parts of the country other than theirs. NYSC, among other aims and objectives was meant to encourage mobility of labour in the country, foster common ties among Nigerian Youths and thereby promote national unity.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OPEC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the main objective of OPEC is to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">assist multinational companies to monopolized market </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protect the interest of multinational companies </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stabilizes the income of developing nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fix and allocate production quotas to member nations </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the major objectives of OPEC is to fix and allocate production quotas to member nations, hence, the quantity to be produced by each member nation is the responsibility of OPEC i.e the country must not exceed a particular quantity.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OPEC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's foreign relation with Britain was strained during the Buhari Regime because </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Britain tested atomic bomb in the Sahara Desert  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Britain refused to recognize the regime </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria refused to export crude oil Britain </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria wanted to forcefully extradite Alhaji Umar Dikko from Britain </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Buhari administration (1983 - 1985) claimed to be an offshoot of the Muritala/Obasanjo regime, but its foreign policy was not as radical and dynamic. The Buhari regime continued with the Shagari policy of expulsion of illegal aliens of West African origin and closure of land borders to stem smuggling and currency trafficking. This strained relationship between Nigeria and her West African Neighbours.  <br/>  Relations with Britain was adversely affected during this period, following the unsuccessful attempt to extradite Alhaji Umaru Dikko (former Transport Minister and Chairman, Presidential Task Force on importation of rice under Shagaris' government) who had been in exile, back to Nigeria.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA'S FOREIGN POLICY : RELATIONS WITH MAJOR POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Babangida Regime differed from the Buhari Regime because in the form that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">governor were assisted by commissioner </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ministers executed government policies </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">governors were members of the National Council of States</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the post of Chairman, Joint Chiefs of staff was created </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Babangida Regime differed from the Buhari Regime in the form that governors were members of the National Council of States. The National Council of States is an advisory body that includes the President, Vice President, all state governors, and former presidents. This was not the case during the Buhari Regime, making it a distinguishing feature of the Babangida Regime.</div>", "topic": "THE MILITARY IN NIGERIAN POLITICS : STRUCTURE OF MILITARY REGIMES"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A feature of the presidential system is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the president has an indefinite term of office </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is a seperate election for the executive and the legislature </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the president is a member of the legislature </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cabinet is collectively accounted to the legislature  </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The presidential system of government is one in which all executive power are vested in one person called the President and in which the executive aim of government is separated from the legislative but equal to it. The USA offers a very good examples of a presidential system of government. Nigeria tried the system from 1979 - 1983 and used it from 1999 till date. One of the features is that the President is elected by the electorate either directly or indirectly through an electoral college and not chosen by the legislature.</div>", "topic": "SYSTEMS OF GOVERNANCE : PRESIDENTIAL SYSTEM OF GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Chairman of the Federal Character Commission is appointed by the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Secretary to the Government of the federation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National Assembly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Minister of Labour and Productivity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">President </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Federal Character Commission (FCC) is a federal executive body established by Act No 34 of 1996 to implement and enforce the federal character principle of fairness and equity in the distribution of public post and socio-economic infrastructures among the various federating units of the Federal Republic of Nigeria. The provisions of the 1999 constitution in section 14 and is 3 unsolidated the establishment of the FCC for operation in a democratic system of government. The President is responsible for the appiontment of the chairman of the FCC</div>", "topic": "INSTITUTIONS OF GOVERNMENT IN THE POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : THE EXECUTIVE – STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND WORKINGS."}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A form of government in which the sovereign power to rule is vested in a small number of people considered as the best qualified to rule is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">autocracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">theocracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gerontocracy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">aristocracy </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aristocracy is government by the best and most qualified people in the state, or by those seen as superior citizens to whom people look upon for leadership. It is government by the privileged few i.e the nobility.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : OLIGARCHY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the major shortcomings of ECOWAS is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">explanation of market </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trade liberalization </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">curbing smuggling </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fostering of unity</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the major shortcomings of ECOWAS is associated with escalation of smuggling which is exacerbated by the free movement of the \"community citizens\". </div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : ECOWAS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The party that formed a coatition with the NPC in the First Republic was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">AG</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NDC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NEPU</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NCNC</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The National Council of Nigeria and Cameroun (NCNC) formed in August 1944 was first named National Council of Nigeria and the Camerouns and later re-named the National Convention of Nigerian citizens in 1960 when the camerouns broke away from Nigeria. The NCNC was the first Nigerian political party to be organised to seek total independence for Nigeria. Herbert Macaulay was the first leader and President of NCNC and Dr Nnamdi Azikiwe, the General Secretary. The NCNC later formed a coalition party with the Northern People's Congress (NPC) during the first republic.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FIRST REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Personal authority is synonymous with </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">charismatic authority </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">instrumental authority </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sacred authority </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">legal authority </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Charismatic authority is one that is based on extraordinary personal qualities of an individual such extraordinary personal qualities of the individual influence others to accept orders of the individual and obey them. It is other known as personal authority.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POWER, AUTHORITY, LEGITIMACY AND SOVEREIGNTY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The administrative system used by the British in her colonies was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indignant system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">direct rule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indirect rule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">policy of assimilation </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Indirect rule may be defined as a British system of ruling her colonies with the use of local chiefs or other appointed intermediaries and traditional laws and customs with British officials merely supervising the administration. Indirect rule was introduced in Nigeria by Sir Lord Lugard who described the system of administration as a \"child of necessity\". Lord Lugard introduced the indirect rule system in Nigeria around 1906 first in Northern Nigeria when he was the High commissioner of the Protectorate of Northern Nigeria.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH COLONIAL ADMINISTRATIVE POLICY – DIRECT AND INDIRECT RULE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An electoral system in which a candidate with the highest number of vote in a constituency is declared winner is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">alternative vote system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">second ballot system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">absolute majority system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">simple majority system  </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In simple majority system or plurality system otherwise called First-Past-The-Post or simple plurality is the type of electoral system in which the candidate with the highest number of votes is declared the winner. It does not mean that elected candidate must secure majority of the votes cast. For instance, if 70,000 voters voted for three candidates in a electoral constituency, thus; *nl <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Canidates</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> Votes</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">A</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">30,000 (the winner)</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">B</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 28,000</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">C</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 12,000</td></tr></table></div>  <br/>  Candidate A is declared the winner because he scored the highest number of votes  and therefore has a plurality. The system is practiced in Nigeria, Ghana, Britain, USA etc.</div>", "topic": "THE ELECTORAL PROCESS : ELECTORAL SYSTEM – TYPES, ADVANTAGES AND DISADVANTAGES OF EACH TYPE."}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following belongs to the administrative cadre in the civil service? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Executive officers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Surveyor </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Medical Directors </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Deputy Directors </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The administrative cadre in the civil service refers to the group of officers who are responsible for the day-to-day administration of the government. This includes roles such as executive officers, who are involved in the implementation of government policies and the management of public resources. Surveyors, Medical Directors, and Deputy Directors are more specialized roles that do not necessarily fall under the administrative cadre.</div>", "topic": "THE CIVIL SERVICE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aristocracy is described as a form of government in which </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">popular citizens rule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the clergy rule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">few citizen rule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">best citizen rule </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aristocracy is government by the best and most qualified in the state or by those seen as superior citizens to whom people look upon for leadership. It is government by the privileged few i.e nobility.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : ARISTOCRACY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The head of the Old Oyo Empire was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Alaafin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bashorun </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oori </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Are-Ona-kakanfo</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The system of government of the old Oyo Empire in the period before 1800, was like most other kingdoms that existed in Africa. It was monarchical in nature, based on the not too easy to run principle of inheritance known as patrilineality. The government of the empire thrived along four major organs, that acted as a check on each other. The King is known as Alaafin of Oyo. He ruled according to the advise of the Oyomesi.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : YORUBA PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Babangida regime re-established diplomatic ties with </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">France </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Germany</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Israel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Britain </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Babangida Era (1985 - 1993): This era launched Nigeria back to the fore front of international relations. The regime introduced economic diplomacy into Nigeria's foreign policy. Nigeria was committed to a functional ECOWAS and this led to Babangida's three years tenure as ECOWAS chairman. His government also re-established diplomatic ties with Israel.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA’S FOREIGN POLICY : RELATIONS WITH MAJOR POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The remote cause of the Action Group Crisis of 1962 was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fear of domination </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abolition of federalism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">personality clash among its leaders </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">issue of self government </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the factors which contributed to the Action Group crisis of 1962 was personality clash between Chief Obafemi Awolowo the party leader and Chief Akintola, his deputy party leader. Chief Awolowo saw Chief S. L Akintola as an over-ambitious and egocentric individual that wanted to supplant him as the leader of the party. This made Chief Awolowo to view his deputy, Chief Akintola, as a traitor who must be removed from the party.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FIRST REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fixed tenure of office is associated with the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">parliamentary system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monarchical system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">republican system </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">presidential system </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Presidential system of government as practised in USA and Nigeria has the tenure of office of the President fixed.</div>", "topic": "SYSTEMS OF GOVERNANCE : PRESIDENTIAL SYSTEM OF GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following was a Revenue Allocation Commission? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Udoji Commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Raisman Commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aboyade Commission </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Willinks Commission </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Aboyade Commission was a Revenue Allocation Commission in Nigeria. It was established in 1977 by the military government to review the existing revenue allocation formula. The commission's recommendations formed the basis for the revenue allocation formula used in Nigeria's Second Republic. The Udoji Commission was a Public Service Review Commission, the Raisman Commission was a Fiscal Commission in India, and the Willinks Commission was a Commission of Inquiry into the Fears of Minorities in Nigeria.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC COMMISSIONS ESTABLISHED BY THE 1979 AND SUBSEQUENT CONSTITUTIONS : ELECTORAL COMMISSIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Election can be used to measure the effectiveness of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pressure groups </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">political propaganda </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">political opinion </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">public opinion </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Election is the act of choosing or selecting candidates who will represent the people of a country in the parliament and in other positions in the government. Election can be used to measure public opinion on certain issues in the country.</div>", "topic": "THE ELECTORAL PROCESS : ELECTION – TYPES, INGREDIENTS OF FREE AND FAIR ELECTION."}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A feature of communalism is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ownership of land is vested in the community </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a landowner can employ landless men </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">landless men have no privileges as citizens </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sovereignty is identified with landed property </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Communalism refers to a system of collective ownership of property and co-operation among members of a community in the execution of development projects. This system of government was more predominant in the pre-colonial era. There was collective ownership of property e.g Land.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : COMMUNALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Hausa pre-colonial, system, the officer in charge of fishing activities was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sarkin Noma</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sarkin Dogaral</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sarkin Ruwa </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sarkin Pawa </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Waziri can be regarded as the senior official and head of administration. Not only that, he is in charge of all ministries and carry out the day to day administrative responsibility on behalf of the Emir. <br/> The Galadima is best known as the administrator of the capital of the emirate. That is, he is in charge of Emir's capital territory. <br/> Madawaki can be regarded as the commander of the Calvary (i.e. Commander of the Army). Specifically, he is known as the Modern Day Chief of Army Staff. <br/> The Dogari is known as the chief of police. In the contemporary world, Dogari is regarded as Inspector-General of Police (IG) whose responsibility is that of security. <br/> Maaji stands as treasurer in charge of treasury. That is, Maaji is in charge of inancial activities just like the Governor of Central Bank. <br/> <strong>Sarkin Ruwa is the minister in charge of fishery</strong>. He organizes fishing festival under the jurisdiction of the Emir. <br/> Sarkin Pawa is the head of butchers. <br/> Sarkin Fada on the other hand is head of Emir's workers. <br/> The emirate system was divided into a number of districts headed by 'Hakimi'. However, Hakimi is regarded as district head whose responsibility is that of tax collector. Tax like Jangali (cattle tax collected by the Hakimi on behalf of the Emir). Hence, he is responsible to the Emir. Other taxes collected are Kharaj on land, Zakat on properties etc.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : HAUSA PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Social and Cultural Affairs Commission is a specialized agency of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OPEC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Commonwealth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">UN</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ECOWAS </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Social and Cultural Affairs Commission is a specialized agency of the United Nations (UN). The UN is an international organization that was founded in 1945 and is composed of 193 member states. The organization is tasked with maintaining international peace and security, promoting sustainable development, protecting human rights, upholding international law, and delivering humanitarian aid. The Social and Cultural Affairs Commission is one of the six main organs of the UN, and it is responsible for promoting higher standards of living, full employment, and conditions of economic and social progress and development.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OPEC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following assists the president in the formulation of Foreign policies?  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministry of Foreign Affairs </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministry of Interior </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministry of Defence </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministry of Justice </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Minister of Foreign Affairs is charged with the responsibility of formulating foreign policies together with the President</div>", "topic": "FOREIGN POLICY : FORMULATION AND IMPLEMENTATION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rule by divine right is a basis of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">absolute monarchy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">representative democracy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the republican system</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the feudal system </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absolute monarchy or despotic monarchy is a monarchical form of government in which the monarch has absolute power among his or her people. An absolute monarch wields unrestricted power over the sovereign state and its people.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : MONARCHY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>2015>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An important ingredient of the civil service is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hierarchy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">imbalance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nepotism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">partisanship </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An important feature of civil service is hierarchy. This implies that promotions are given as at when due and there is an organogram guiding the civil service.</div>", "topic": "THE CIVIL SERVICE : CHARACTERISTICS AND FUNCTIONS"}];
